**The Recipe for Happy Cats**

&NewLine;

_Huom! Tässä tehtävässä emme valitettavasti voi tarjota oikeita vastauksia._

&NewLine;

You may be surprised to learn that 45 per cent of UK cat-owning households have more than one cat – and if [GAP id=1] is one of them, you’ll know how stressful mealtimes can be for them – and for you! If your cats are at different life stages, or one is overweight and one is thin, it can be pretty tricky making sure each individual pet [GAP id=2] the most nutritious food [GAP id=3] its age and health.

&NewLine;

Food is not the only area that can cause problems for the modern feline in a multi-cat household. Homes have become much less cat-friendly of late, with the fashion for minimalism meaning that [GAP id=4] harder for cats to find cosy corners or good vantage points from which [GAP id=5] their surroundings.

&NewLine;

Jan Cisek says, ‘A happy cat really does equal a happy owner and a happy home.’ For example, owners should place several food stations around the house [GAP id=6] their cats to follow natural grazing patterns. Cat owners should also think about swapping leather furniture for softer fabrics to instill a sense of [GAP id=7] and relaxation in their pets.

&NewLine;

Here are some tips to transform your household into a feline home:

– Don’t be too tidy. Cats actually like a bit of clutter as they love to hide and explore in nooks and crannies.

– Don’t place [GAP id=8] food and water bowls [GAP id=9].

– Cats like these elements to be separate – this will also make them want to drink more from their bowls and less from the tap!

– Make sure you create some power positions for your cats. Places that are high up, from where they can observe their world, make for a truly [GAP id=10] animal. [CITE source=BBC Good Food, 2007]

